    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1973-06-04T10:50:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1973-06-04T08:15:00-05:00" n="156"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d156">
                <head>156. Memorandum of Conversation<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d156fn1"
                        >Source: Ford Library, <persName corresp="#p_KHA1"
                            >Kissinger</persName>–<persName corresp="#p_SB3">Scowcroft</persName>
                        West Wing Office Files, Box 23, United Kingdom (5). Top Secret; Sensitive;
                        Exclusively Eyes Only. The conversation took place in the United Kingdom
                        Embassy Chancery.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            from="1973-06-04T09:15:00-04:00" to="1973-06-04T11:50:00-04:00"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date">June 4, 1973, 9:15–11:50 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_TSB1">Sir Burke Trend</persName>, Secretary to the
                        Cabinet</item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_CEGRSB1">Earl of Cromer</persName>, <gloss
                            target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> Ambassador</item>
                    <item>
                        <persName>Richard Sykes</persName>, Minister</item>
                    <item>
                        <persName>Charles Powell</persName>, First Secretary</item>
                    <item>Dr. <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Henry A. Kissinger</persName>, Assistant
                        to the President for National Security Affairs</item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SHH1">Helmut Sonnenfeldt</persName>, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Senior Staff</item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HWG1">William Hyland</persName>, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Senior Staff</item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RPW1">Peter W. Rodman</persName>, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Staff</item>
                </list>
                <p>[Omitted here is discussion of matters other than the European security
                    conference or <gloss target="#t_MBFR1">MBFR</gloss>.]</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_TSB1">Trend</persName>: On <gloss target="#t_MBFR1"
                        >MBFR</gloss>, are we back in your good books?</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>: I haven’t heard any complaints
                    lately.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_TSB1">Trend</persName>: You were so unhappy last time we
                        met.<note n="2" xml:id="d156fn2">See <ref target="#d140">Document
                        140</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>: You should be aware of one
                    thing the Russians have proposed to us, on <gloss target="#t_MBFR1">MBFR</gloss>
                    and <gloss target="#t_CSCE1">CSCE</gloss>. I am beginning to think I understand
                    the Asian mind better than the European mind! Last year the Europeans were
                    complaining we had to set a date for the opening of <gloss target="#t_MBFR1"
                        >MBFR</gloss>; now they are complaining we are trying to delay it.</p>
                <p>As I told you, at <persName>Zavidovo Gromyko</persName> said it was academic
                    because <gloss target="#t_CSCE1">CSCE</gloss> would be over by the end of
                    September. Now they said if we <pb facs="0516" n="481" xml:id="pg_481"/> agree
                    to end <gloss target="#t_CSCE1">CSCE</gloss> this year, they will agree to fix a
                    date for the <gloss target="#t_MBFR1">MBFR</gloss> opening even if it is prior
                    to the closing of <gloss target="#t_CSCE1">CSCE</gloss>. This is the proposition
                    they put to me.<note n="3" xml:id="d156fn3">See <ref target="#d155">Document
                            155</ref>.</note> I understand <persName corresp="#p_BWHF1"
                        >Brandt</persName> is willing to end <gloss target="#t_CSCE1">CSCE</gloss>
                    this year.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_SR3">Sykes</persName>: Three to four months may be needed,
                    on the commissions. But we really can not fix a date because we don’t know how
                    it will go.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>: What would you say if we had a
                    vague phrase in our Communiqué<note n="4" xml:id="d156fn4">Apparent reference to
                        the joint communiqué for <persName corresp="#p_BLI1">Brezhnev</persName>’s
                        upcoming visit; see <ref target="#d163">Document 163</ref>.</note> that we
                    don’t oppose ending <gloss target="#t_CSCE1">CSCE</gloss> this year, or
                    something like that?</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_SR3">Sykes</persName>: I don’t think you should do that;
                    you will become a hostage.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>: We don’t care about <gloss
                        target="#t_CSCE1">CSCE</gloss>. But would it be worth some small price in
                    order to get <gloss target="#t_MBFR1">MBFR</gloss>?</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_CEGRSB1">Cromer</persName>: If it is just set as an
                    objective, there is no price.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>: But <gloss target="#t_CSCE1"
                        >CSCE</gloss> now need not be over first. We have to have <gloss
                        target="#t_MBFR1">MBFR</gloss> discussions going on when Congress reconvenes
                    next January. You know this.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_SR3">Sykes</persName>: Yes.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_CEGRSB1">Cromer</persName>: The question is whether the
                    Russians want a definitive date of before the end of this year.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>: A definitive date would be
                    impossible to deliver.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_SR3">Sykes</persName>: I don’t see how London would object
                    to setting a date as an objective, if <gloss target="#t_MBFR1">MBFR</gloss> can
                    begin before.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>: Could you get me an
                    answer?</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_SR3">Sykes</persName>: Yes.</p>
                <p>[Omitted here is discussion of matters other than the European security
                    conference or <gloss target="#t_MBFR1">MBFR</gloss>.]</p>
            </div>
